            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kai Jones\u2019 story is one of fusion, both in his heritage and his passions. The only child of a meticulous African American Air Force officer and a creative Japanese mother, Kai\u2019s childhood in Sacramento was a blend of discipline and artistry. His father taught him logistics and the value of a well-executed plan, while his mother introduced him to the complex, soulful language of food, where every ingredient had a purpose and every meal told a story. Weekend trips to San Francisco were a formative ritual, exposing him to a culinary world that felt limitless and electric.\n\nThis early exposure naturally led him to pursue a Hospitality degree at San Francisco State University. While he excelled in his studies, a grueling part-time job as a host at a Michelin-starred restaurant in Hayes Valley became his true crucible. There, he realized he wasn\u2019t meant for the front lines of service; his talent was in seeing the bigger picture. He had a natural gift for understanding how a restaurant\u2019s brand could extend beyond its four walls, and he shifted his focus toward strategic growth. This insight landed him his current role as a Restaurant Partnership Manager, where he brokers deals to bring his company's culinary concepts into arts and entertainment venues across the city.\n\nNow 29, Kai lives a life deeply woven into the fabric of San Francisco. He resides in a rent-controlled apartment in the Mission District, a neighborhood whose vibrant energy he thrives on. His daily 3.8-mile bike commute to his SoMa office is a cherished routine, a blur of colorful murals, the aroma of bakeries, and the city waking up. His social life, recently freed from a long-term relationship, revolves around a close-knit circle of industry friends and his cycling group. Evenings are spent exploring new pop-ups, deconstructing menus, or catching shows at venues he partners with.\n\nKai feels a profound connection to San Francisco, seeing it as the only place that could accommodate his unique ambitions. While he\u2019s proud of his career, his ultimate dream is to create something of his own. He envisions opening a small, intimate eatery that reflects his own story\u2014a Japanese-style izakaya infused with the flavors and traditions of American soul food. For Kai, this isn't just a business plan; it's the ultimate expression of his identity, a chance to build a legacy, one plate at a time, in the city that feels like home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being eleven, wedged between his mother and father in a tiny Japantown ramen shop. The air was thick with steam and the chefs moved with a beautiful, controlled chaos his father would admire. The rich, salty pork broth was unlike anything his mother made, yet felt just as soulful. He slurped his noodles, feeling the city\u2019s electric energy for the first time. In that moment, he knew his life would be about food\u2014not just making it, but understanding its story. This memory became his compass, always pointing toward San Francisco.\n\n2.\nAt twenty, during a brutal Saturday service at the Hayes Valley restaurant, he felt himself breaking. A VIP\u2019s reservation was lost, and the manager\u2019s fury was a cold weight. Hiding in the back, Kai looked at the dining room not as a collection of tables, but as a complex machine\u2014a living, breathing brand. He didn't want to be a cog in that machine; he wanted to be its architect. The panic subsided, replaced by a clarifying calm. It was the night he stopped wanting to serve and started wanting to build.\n\n3.\nIt was his first major partnership deal at 27: placing a modern taqueria concept inside the SFJAZZ Center. On opening night, he stood in the atrium, watching people sway to a saxophone solo with tacos in hand. The music, the architecture, the food\u2014it all flowed together into one seamless, elevated experience. It wasn\u2019t just a business deal; it was a perfectly executed plan, a synthesis of art and logistics. He felt a profound sense of validation, knowing this was the work he was meant to do.\n\n4.\nHe was on the phone with his mother last year, nervously trying to explain his dream. \u201cIt\u2019s like an izakaya,\u201d he started, \u201cbut with soul food flavors.\u201d He then pictured a specific dish: karaage, his mother\u2019s crisp Japanese fried chicken, but seasoned with the secret Cajun spice blend his father used for Sunday dinners. A jolt went through him. It wasn't just an idea anymore; it was his entire identity on a plate. That single dish crystallized his ambition, making the abstract dream feel real, urgent, and entirely his own.\n\n5.\nA few months ago, just after the breakup, his morning bike commute felt different. The Mission fog was thick, blurring the murals on Clarion Alley. As he pedaled, the sweet scent of baking bread from La Reyna Bakery hit him, mingling with the damp, earthy smell of the park. It was a moment of profound, grounding comfort. The city wasn't just a backdrop; it was a constant, holding him steady while his own world shifted. He felt a quiet sense of belonging, realizing he was already home."
